🏗 Section 7: Quality, Bugs & Defect Governance

Role & Purpose in the Manual
	•	This is the quality guardrail section: it defines how defects and leakages are handled in disciplined fashion.
	•	It connects requirement discipline (AC → tests) with delivery integrity (bugs, regression) and governs expectations realistically.
	•	It ensures that quality is not an afterthought but a monitored artifact with metrics, dashboards, and trade-off gates.
	•	It also protects the Delivery Team from unrealistic demands (e.g. “100% bug-free”) by providing frameworks for commitment, negotiation, and visibility.

⸻

🎯 Promise: What This Section Will Deliver

By the end of Section 7, the reader will:
	•	Hold a realistic mindset about quality (not myth of zero defects).
	•	Be able to tie every defect to acceptance criteria or risk surfaces, so you avoid “unowned” bugs.
	•	Understand how to build a test automation strategy — where to invest and where not to.
	•	Know the key quality metrics / SLIs / SLOs / error budgets to monitor health and enforce gates.
	•	Have dashboards, alert rules, and audience segmentation to make quality visible.
	•	Be equipped to negotiate contractual commitments around quality (what you can promise, what you can’t).
	•	Have guardrails to refuse unqualified “bug-free” demands without losing credibility.

