⚙️ Guidance to the Reader: VP Coaching on Quality Governance
	1.	Reject the Illusion of Zero Bugs Politely
	•	Never promise perfection. Instead promise bounded risk.
	•	If stakeholders demand 0 defects, push for alignment: What risk level is acceptable?
	2.	Always Link Defects back to Acceptance Criteria / Risk Surfaces
	•	When a defect is filed, force the question: Which AC or NFR did we miss or mis-specify?
	•	This links back to requirements discipline and avoids mysterious bugs.
	3.	Prioritize Automations Based on Risk & Frequency, Not Vanity Metrics
	•	Automate the 20–30% of flows that cover 80% of use.
	•	Use flake, failure rate, frequency signals to guide where automation investment brings most ROI.
	4.	Build Quality Gates, Not Quality Checkpoints
	•	Have pass/fail criteria before releases (leakage threshold, error budget remaining).
	•	Don’t treat QA as optional — architect delivery around the gate.
	5.	Use Dashboards as Safety Alarms, Not Blame Tools
	•	Expose trends early (rising leakage, high flake) so teams remediate before release.
	•	Use alerts as signals to raise conversation, not alarms to deploy blame.
	6.	Use Error Budgets as Communication Filters
	•	Once error budget is consumed, features must pause, debt or stabilization prioritized.
	•	This gives you a clean, evidence-based reason to say “no more features now.”
	7.	Negotiate Realistic Quality Commitments in Contracts
	•	Make quality obligations conditional (e.g. “defects resolved within X hours except when defect budget exceeded”).
	•	Maintain exclusions for third-party interfaces, ambiguous requirements, unknown dependencies.
	8.	Reassess Quality Strategy Periodically
	•	Review defect leakage versus automation effectiveness regularly.
	•	Evolve your SLOs and gates as systems mature.

